To make Claude return citations for its answers, you need to enable citations on the documents you provide to Claude. Currently, citations must be enabled on all or none of the documents within a request.

Here's an example of how to enable citations on a document:

```json
{
  "type": "document",
  "source": {
    "type": "text",
    "media_type": "text/plain",
    "data": "The grass is green. The sky is blue."
  },
  "title": "My Document",
  "context": "This is a trustworthy document.",
  "citations": {"enabled": true}
}
```

You can also use the CLI or Python client to enable citations. Here's an example using the Python client:

```python
import anthropic

client = anthropic.Anthropic()

response = client.messages.create(
    model="claude-opus-4-7",
    max_tokens=1024,
    messages=[
        {
            "role": "user",
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "document",
                    "source": {
                        "type": "text",
                        "media_type": "text/plain",
                        "data": "The grass is green. The sky is blue."
                    },
                    "title": "My Document",
                    "context": "This is a trustworthy document.",
                    "citations": {"enabled": true}
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
)
```

Note that only text citations are currently supported, and image citations are not yet possible.

The MCP connector is a feature in the Claude API that enables you to connect to remote Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers directly from the Messages API without a separate MCP client [1][2]. This allows you to access MCP tools and data sources through a standardized protocol.

To use the MCP connector, you need to include the MCP server definition (`mcp_servers` array) and the MCP toolset (`tools` array) in your API request [3]. The MCP server definition specifies the connection details, such as the URL and authentication token, while the MCP toolset configures which tools to enable and how to configure them.

Here's an example of how to use the MCP connector in your API request:

```json
{
  "model": "claude-opus-4-7",
  "max_tokens": 1000,
  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Use tools from both mcp-server-1 and mcp-server-2 to complete this task"
    }
  ],
  "mcp_servers": [
    {
      "type": "url",
      "url": "https://mcp.example1.com/sse",
      "name": "mcp-server-1",
      "authorization_token": "TOKEN1"
    },
    {
      "type": "url",
      "url": "https://mcp.example2.com/sse",
      "name": "mcp-server-2",
      "authorization_token": "TOKEN2"
    }
  ],
  "tools": [
    {
      "type": "mcp_toolset",
      "mcp_server_name": "mcp-server-1"
    },
    {
      "type": "mcp_toolset",
      "mcp_server_name": "mcp-server-2",
      "default_config": {
        "defer_loading": true
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

Note that the MCP connector requires the beta header `"anthropic-beta": "mcp-client-2025-11-20"` and is not eligible for Zero Data Retention (ZDR) [2].
